# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thermal-management-electronics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] In computers, heat sinks are used to cool CPUs, GPUs, and some chipsets and RAM modules.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Heat sinks are used with other high-power semiconductor devices such as power transistors and optoelectronics such as lasers and light-emitting diodes (LEDs), where the heat dissipation ability of the component itself is insufficient to moderate its temperature.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A heat sink is designed to maximize its surface area in contact with the cooling medium surrounding it, such as the air.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Air velocity, choice of material, protrusion design and surface treatment are factors that affect the performance of a heat sink.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Heat sink attachment methods and thermal interface materials also affect the die temperature of the integrated circuit.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Thermal adhesive or thermal paste improve the heat sink's performance by filling air gaps between the heat sink and the heat spreader on the device.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A heat sink is usually made out of a material with a high thermal conductivity, such as aluminium or copper.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A heat sink transfers thermal energy from a higher-temperature device to a lower-temperature fluid medium.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The fluid medium is frequently air, but can also be water, refrigerants, or even oil.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] If the fluid medium is water, the heat sink is frequently called a cold plate.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] In thermodynamics a heat sink is a heat reservoir that can absorb an arbitrary amount of heat without significantly changing temperature.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Practical heat sinks for electronic devices must have a temperature higher than the surroundings to transfer heat by convection, radiation, and conduction.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The power supplies of electronics are not absolutely efficient, so extra heat is produced that may be detrimental to the function of the device.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] As such, a heat sink is included in the design to disperse heat.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Fourier's law of heat conduction shows that when there is a temperature gradient in a body, heat will be transferred from the higher-temperature region to the lower-temperature region.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The rate at which heat is transferred by conduction, $q_{k}$ , is proportional to the product of the temperature gradient and the cross-sectional area through which heat is transferred.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] For a heat sink in a duct, where air flows through the duct, the heat-sink base will usually be hotter than the air flowing through the duct.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Using the mean air temperature is an assumption that is valid for relatively short heat sinks.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] When compact heat exchangers are calculated, the logarithmic mean air temperature is used.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Natural convection requires free flow of air over the heat sink.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] If fins are not aligned vertically, or if fins are too close together to allow sufficient air flow between them, the efficiency of the heat sink will decline.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] For semiconductor devices used in a variety of consumer and industrial electronics, the idea of *thermal resistance* simplifies the selection of heat sinks.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The heat flow between the semiconductor die and ambient air is modeled as a series of resistances to heat flow; there is a resistance from the die to the device case, from the case to the heat sink, and from the heat sink to the ambient air.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The sum of these resistances is the total thermal resistance from the die to the ambient air.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Thermal resistance is defined as temperature rise per unit of power, analogous to electrical resistance, and is expressed in units of degrees Celsius per watt (°C/W).
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] If the device dissipation in watts is known, and the total thermal resistance is calculated, the temperature rise of the die over the ambient air can be calculated.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The idea of thermal resistance of a semiconductor heat sink is an approximation.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] It does not take into account non-uniform distribution of heat over a device or heat sink.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] It only models a system in thermal equilibrium and does not take into account the change in temperatures with time.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Nor does it reflect the non-linearity of radiation and convection with respect to temperature rise.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] However, manufacturers tabulate typical values of thermal resistance for heat sinks and semiconductor devices, which allows selection of commercially manufactured heat sinks to be simplified.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Commercial extruded aluminium heat sinks have a thermal resistance (heat sink to ambient air) ranging from 0.4 °C/W for a large sink meant for TO-3 devices, up to as high as 85 °C/W for a clip-on heat sink for a TO-92 small plastic case.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The popular 2N3055 power transistor in a TO-3 case has an internal thermal resistance from junction to case of 1.52 °C/W.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The contact between the device case and heat sink may have a thermal resistance between 0.5 and 1.7 °C/W, depending on the case size and use of grease or insulating mica washer.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The materials for heat sink applications should have high heat capacity and thermal conductivity in order to absorb more heat energy without shifting towards a very high temperature and transmit it to the environment for efficient cooling.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The most common heat sink materials are aluminium alloys.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Aluminium alloy 1050 has one of the higher thermal conductivity values at 229 W/(m·K) and heat capacity of 922 J/(kg·K), but is mechanically soft.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Aluminium alloys 6060 (low-stress), 6061, and 6063 are commonly used, with thermal conductivity values of 166 and 201 W/(m·K) respectively.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The values depend on the temper of the alloy.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] One-piece aluminium heat sinks can be made by extrusion, casting, skiving or milling.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Copper has excellent heat-sink properties in terms of its thermal conductivity, corrosion resistance, biofouling resistance, and antimicrobial resistance (see also Copper in heat exchangers).
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Copper has around twice the thermal conductivity of aluminium, around 400 W/(m·K) for pure copper.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Its main applications are in industrial facilities, power plants, solar thermal water systems, HVAC systems, gas water heaters, forced air heating and cooling systems, geothermal heating and cooling, and electronic systems.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Copper is three times as dense and more expensive than aluminium, and copper is less ductile than aluminum.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] One-piece copper heat sinks can be made by skiving or milling.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Sheet-metal fins can be soldered onto a rectangular copper body.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Fin efficiency is one of the parameters that makes a higher-thermal-conductivity material important.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A fin of a heat sink may be considered to be a flat plate with heat flowing in one end and being dissipated into the surrounding fluid as it travels to the other.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] As heat flows through the fin, the combination of the thermal resistance of the heat sink impeding the flow and the heat lost due to convection, the temperature of the fin and, therefore, the heat transfer to the fluid, will decrease from the base to the end of the fin.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Fin efficiency is defined as the actual heat transferred by the fin, divided by the heat transfer were the fin to be isothermal (hypothetically the fin having infinite thermal conductivity).
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Fin efficiency is increased by decreasing the fin aspect ratio (making them thicker or shorter), or by using a more conductive material (copper instead of aluminium, for example).
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Another parameter that concerns the thermal conductivity of the heat-sink material is spreading resistance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Spreading resistance occurs when thermal energy is transferred from a small area to a larger area in a substance with finite thermal conductivity.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] In a heat sink, this means that heat does not distribute uniformly through the heat-sink base.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The spreading resistance phenomenon is shown by how the heat travels from the heat source location and causes a large temperature gradient between the heat source and the edges of the heat sink.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] This means that some fins are at a lower temperature than if the heat source were uniform across the base of the heat sink.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] This nonuniformity increases the heat sink's effective thermal resistance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A pin fin heat sink is a heat sink that has pins that extend from its base.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The pins can be cylindrical, elliptical, or square.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A second type of heat sink fin arrangement is the straight fin.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A variation on the straight fin heat sink is a cross-cut heat sink.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A third type of heat sink is the flared fin heat sink, where the fins are not parallel to one another.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Flaring the fins decreases flow resistance and makes more air go through the heat-sink fin channel; otherwise, more air would bypass the fins.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Slanting them keeps the overall dimensions the same, but offers longer fins.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Examples of the three types are shown in the image on the right.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Forghan, et al. have published data on tests conducted on pin fin, straight fin, and flared fin heat sinks.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] They found that for low air approach velocity, typically around 1 m/s, the thermal performance is at least 20% better than straight fin heat sinks.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Lasance and Eggink also found that for the bypass configurations that they tested, the flared heat sink performed better than the other heat sinks tested.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Generally, the more surface area a heat sink has, the better its performance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Real-world performance depends on the design and application.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The concept of a pin fin heat sink is to pack as much surface area into a given volume as possible, while working in any orientation of fluid flow.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Kordyban has compared the performance of a pin-fin and a straight-fin heat sink of similar dimensions.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Although the pin-fin has 194 cm2 surface area while the straight-fin has 58 cm2, the temperature difference between the heat-sink base and the ambient air for the pin fin is 50 °C, but for the straight-fin it was 44 °C, or 6 °C better than the pin fin.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Pin fin heat sink performance is significantly better than straight fins when used in their optimal application where the fluid flows axially along the pins rather than only tangentially across the pins.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Cavities (inverted fins) embedded in a heat source are the regions formed between adjacent fins that stand for the essential promoters of nucleate boiling or condensation.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] These cavities are usually utilized to extract heat from a variety of heat-generating bodies to a heat sink.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Placing a conductive thick plate as a heat-transfer interface between a heat source and a cold flowing fluid (or any other heat sink) may improve the cooling performance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] In such arrangement, the heat source is cooled under the thick plate instead of being cooled in direct contact with the cooling fluid.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] It is shown that the thick plate can significantly improve the heat transfer between the heat source and the cooling fluid by conducting the heat current in an optimal manner.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The two most attractive advantages of this method are that no additional pumping power and no extra heat-transfer surface area, that is quite different from fins (extended surfaces).
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The heat transfer from the heat sink occurs by convection of the surrounding air, conduction through the air, and radiation.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Heat transfer by radiation is a function of both the heat-sink temperature and the temperature of the surroundings that the heat sink is optically coupled with.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] When both of these temperatures are on the order of 0 °C to 100 °C, the contribution of radiation compared to convection is generally small, and this factor is often neglected.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] In this case, finned heat sinks operating in either natural-convection or forced-flow will not be affected significantly by surface emissivity.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] In situations where convection is low, such as a flat non-finned panel with low airflow, radiative cooling can be a significant factor.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Here the surface properties may be an important design factor.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Matte-black surfaces radiate much more efficiently than shiny bare metal.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A shiny metal surface has low emissivity.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The emissivity of a material is tremendously frequency-dependent and is related to absorptivity (of which shiny metal surfaces have very little).
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] For most materials, the emissivity in the visible spectrum is similar to the emissivity in the infrared spectrum; however, there are exceptions – notably, certain metal oxides that are used as "selective surfaces".
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] In vacuum or outer space, there is no convective heat transfer, thus in these environments, radiation is the only factor governing heat flow between the heat sink and the environment.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] For a satellite in space, a 100 °C (373 K) surface facing the Sun will absorb a lot of radiant heat, because the Sun's surface temperature is nearly 6000 K, whereas the same surface facing deep space will radiate a lot of heat, since deep space has an effective temperature of only several Kelvin.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Heat dissipation is an unavoidable by-product of electronic devices and circuits.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] In general, the temperature of the device or component will depend on the thermal resistance from the component to the environment, and the heat dissipated by the component.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] To ensure that the component does not overheat, a thermal engineer seeks to find an efficient heat transfer path from the device to the environment.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The heat transfer path may be from the component to a printed circuit board (PCB), to a heat sink, to air flow provided by a fan, but in all instances, eventually to the environment.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] For each interface between two objects in contact with each other, there will be a temperature drop across the interface.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] For such composite systems, the temperature drop across the interface may be appreciable.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] This temperature change may be attributed to what is known as the thermal contact resistance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] *Thermal interface materials* (TIM) decrease the thermal contact resistance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] As power dissipation of components increases and component package size decreases, thermal engineers must innovate to ensure components won't overheat.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A heat sink design must fulfill both its thermal as well as its mechanical requirements.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Concerning the latter, the component must remain in thermal contact with its heat sink with reasonable shock and vibration.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The heat sink could be the copper foil of a circuit board, or a separate heat sink mounted onto the component or circuit board.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Attachment methods include thermally conductive tape or epoxy, wire-form z clips, flat spring clips, standoff spacers, and push pins with ends that expand after installing.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Thermally conductive tape is one of the most cost-effective heat sink attachment materials.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] It is suitable for low-mass heat sinks and for components with low power dissipation.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] It consists of a thermally conductive carrier material with a pressure-sensitive adhesive on each side.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] This tape is applied to the base of the heat sink, which is then attached to the component.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Preload pressure is essential to ensure good contact.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Insufficient pressure results in areas of non-contact with trapped air, and results in higher-than-expected interface thermal resistance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Thicker tapes tend to provide better "wettability" with uneven component surfaces.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] "Wettability" is the percentage area of contact of a tape on a component.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Thicker tapes, however, have a higher thermal resistance than thinner tapes.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] From a design standpoint, it is best to strike a balance by selecting a tape thickness that provides maximum "wettability" with minimum thermal resistance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Epoxy is more expensive than tape, but provides a greater mechanical bond between the heat sink and component, as well as improved thermal conductivity.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The epoxy chosen must be formulated for this purpose.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Most epoxies are two-part liquid formulations that must be thoroughly mixed before being applied to the heat sink, and before the heat sink is placed on the component.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The epoxy is then cured for a specified time, which can vary from 2 hours to 48 hours.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Faster cure time can be achieved at higher temperatures.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The surfaces to which the epoxy is applied must be clean and free of any residue.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The epoxy bond between the heat sink and component is semi-permanent/permanent.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] This makes re-work very difficult and at times impossible.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The most typical damage caused by rework is the separation of the component die heat spreader from its package.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] More expensive than tape and epoxy, wire form z-clips attach heat sinks mechanically.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] To use the z-clips, the printed circuit board must have anchors.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Anchors can be either soldered onto the board, or pushed through.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Either type requires holes to be designed into the board.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The use of RoHS solder must be allowed for because such solder is mechanically weaker than traditional Pb/Sn solder.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] To assemble with a z-clip, attach one side of it to one of the anchors.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Deflect the spring until the other side of the clip can be placed in the other anchor.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The deflection develops a spring load on the component, which maintains very good contact.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] In addition to the mechanical attachment that the z-clip provides, it also permits using higher-performance thermal interface materials, such as phase change types.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Available for processors and ball grid array (BGA) components, clips allow the attachment of a BGA heat sink directly to the component.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The clips make use of the gap created by the ball grid array (BGA) between the component underside and PCB top surface.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The clips therefore require no holes in the PCB.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] They also allow for easy rework of components.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] For larger heat sinks and higher preloads, push pins with compression springs are very effective.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The push pins, typically made of brass or plastic, have a flexible barb at the end that engages with a hole in the PCB; once installed, the barb retains the pin.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The compression spring holds the assembly together and maintains contact between the heat sink and component.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Care is needed in selection of push pin size.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Too great an insertion force can result in the die cracking and consequent component failure.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] For very large heat sinks, there is no substitute for the threaded standoff and compression spring attachment method.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A threaded standoff is essentially a hollow metal tube with internal threads.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] One end is secured with a screw through a hole in the PCB.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The other end accepts a screw which compresses the spring, completing the assembly.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A typical heat sink assembly uses two to four standoffs, which tends to make this the most costly heat sink attachment design.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Another disadvantage is the need for holes in the PCB.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Thermal contact resistance occurs due to the voids created by surface roughness effects, defects and misalignment of the interface.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The voids present in the interface are filled with air.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Heat transfer is therefore due to conduction across the actual contact area and to conduction (or natural convection) and radiation across the gaps.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] If the contact area is small, as it is for rough surfaces, the major contribution to the resistance is made by the gaps.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] To decrease the thermal contact resistance, the surface roughness can be decreased while the interface pressure is increased.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] However, these improving methods are not always practical or possible for electronic equipment.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Thermal interface materials (TIM) are a common way to overcome these limitations.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Properly applied thermal interface materials displace the air that is present in the gaps between the two objects with a material that has a much-higher thermal conductivity.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Air has a thermal conductivity of 0.022 W/(m·K) while TIMs have conductivities of 0.3 W/(m·K) and higher.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] When selecting a TIM, care must be taken with the values supplied by the manufacturer.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Most manufacturers give a value for the thermal conductivity of a material.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] However, the thermal conductivity does not take into account the interface resistances.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Therefore, if a TIM has a high thermal conductivity, it does not necessarily mean that the interface resistance will be low.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Selection of a TIM is based on three parameters: the interface gap which the TIM must fill, the contact pressure, and the electrical resistivity of the TIM.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The contact pressure is the pressure applied to the interface between the two materials.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The selection does not include the cost of the material.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Electrical resistivity may be important depending upon electrical design details.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Light-emitting diode (LED) performance and lifetime are strong functions of their temperature.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Effective cooling is therefore essential.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A case study of a LED based downlighter shows an example of the calculations done in order to calculate the required heat sink necessary for the effective cooling of lighting system.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The article also shows that in order to get confidence in the results, multiple independent solutions are required that give similar results.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Specifically, results of the experimental, numerical and theoretical methods should all be within 10% of each other to give high confidence in the results.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Temporary heat sinks are sometimes used while soldering circuit boards, preventing excessive heat from damaging sensitive nearby electronics.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] In the simplest case, this means partially gripping a component using a heavy metal crocodile clip, hemostat, or similar clamp.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Modern semiconductor devices, which are designed to be assembled by reflow soldering, can usually tolerate soldering temperatures without damage.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] On the other hand, electrical components such as magnetic reed switches can malfunction if exposed to hotter soldering irons, so this practice is still very much in use.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] In general, a heat sink performance is a function of material thermal conductivity, dimensions, fin type, heat transfer coefficient, air flow rate, and duct size.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] To determine the thermal performance of a heat sink, a theoretical model can be made.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Alternatively, the thermal performance can be measured experimentally.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Due to the complex nature of the highly 3D flow in present applications, numerical methods or computational fluid dynamics (CFD) can also be used.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] This section will discuss the aforementioned methods for the determination of the heat sink thermal performance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] One of the methods to determine the performance of a heat sink is to use heat transfer and fluid dynamics theory.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] One such method has been published by Jeggels, et al., though this work is limited to ducted flow.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Ducted flow is where the air is forced to flow through a channel which fits tightly over the heat sink.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] This makes sure that all the air goes through the channels formed by the fins of the heat sink.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] When the air flow is not ducted, a certain percentage of air flow will bypass the heat sink.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Flow bypass was found to increase with increasing fin density and clearance, while remaining relatively insensitive to inlet duct velocity.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The heat sink thermal resistance model consists of two resistances, namely the resistance in the heat sink base, $R_{b}$ , and the resistance in the fins, $R_{f}$ .
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The heat sink base thermal resistance, $R_{b}$ , can be written as follows if the source is a uniformly applied the heat sink base.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] where $t_{b}$ is the heat sink base thickness, k is the heat sink material thermal conductivity and $A_{b}$ is the area of the heat sink base.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The flow rate can be determined by the intersection of the heat sink system curve and the fan curve.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The heat sink system curve can be calculated by the flow resistance of the channels and inlet and outlet losses as done in standard fluid mechanics text books, such as Potter, et al. and White.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Using the equations 5 to 13 and the dimensional data in, the thermal resistance for the fins was calculated for various air flow rates.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The data for the thermal resistance and heat transfer coefficient are shown in the diagram, which shows that for an increasing air flow rate, the thermal resistance of the heat sink decreases.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Experimental tests are one of the more popular ways to determine the heat sink thermal performance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] In order to determine the heat sink thermal resistance, the flow rate, input power, inlet air temperature and heat sink base temperature need to be known.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Vendor-supplied data is commonly provided for ducted test results.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] However, the results are optimistic and can give misleading data when heat sinks are used in an unducted application.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] More details on heat sink testing methods and common oversights can be found in Azar, et al.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] In industry, thermal analyses are often ignored in the design process or performed too late — when design changes are limited and become too costly.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Of the three methods mentioned in this article, theoretical and numerical methods can be used to determine an estimate of the heat sink or component temperatures of products before a physical model has been made.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] A theoretical model is normally used as a first order estimate.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Online heat sink calculators can provide a reasonable estimate of forced and natural convection heat sink performance based on a combination of theoretical and empirically derived correlations.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Numerical methods or computational fluid dynamics (CFD) provide a qualitative (and sometimes even quantitative) prediction of fluid flows.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] What this means is that it will give a visual or post-processed result of a simulation, like the images in figures 16 and 17, and the CFD animations in figure 18 and 19, but the quantitative or absolute accuracy of the result is sensitive to the inclusion and accuracy of the appropriate parameters.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] CFD can give an insight into flow patterns that are difficult, expensive or impossible to study using experimental methods.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Experiments can give a quantitative description of flow phenomena using measurements for one quantity at a time, at a limited number of points and time instances.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] If a full-scale model is not available or not practical, scale models or dummy models can be used.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] The experiments can have a limited range of problems and operating conditions.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] Simulations can give a prediction of flow phenomena using CFD software for all desired quantities, with high resolution in space and time and virtually any problem and realistic operating conditions.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/heat-sink] However, if critical, the results may need to be validated.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] Various physical properties of semiconductor materials are temperature dependent.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] These include the diffusion rate of dopant elements, carrier mobilities and the thermal production of charge carriers.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] At the low end, sensor diode noise can be reduced by cryogenic cooling.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] On the high end, the resulting increase in local power dissipation can lead to thermal runaway that may cause transient or permanent device failure.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] In modern processors from manufacturers such as Intel, AMD, Qualcomm, the core temperature is measured by a network of sensors.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] If the applied mechanisms are not compensating enough for the processor to stay below the junction temperature, the device may shut down to prevent permanent damage.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] Many semiconductors and their surrounding optics are small, making it difficult to measure junction temperature with direct methods such as thermocouples and infrared cameras.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] Junction temperature may be measured indirectly using the device's inherent voltage/temperature dependency characteristic.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] Combined with a Joint Electron Device Engineering Council (JEDEC) technique such as JESD 51-1 and JESD 51-51, this method will produce accurate $T_{J}$ measurements.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] However, this measurement technique is difficult to implement in multi-LED series circuits due to high common mode voltages and the need for fast, high duty cycle current pulses.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] This difficulty can be overcome by combining high-speed sampling digital multimeters and fast high-compliance pulsed current sources.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] An LED or laser diode’s junction temperature (Tj) is a primary determinate for long-term reliability; it also is a key factor for photometry.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] For example, a typical white LED output declines 20% for a 50 °C rise in junction temperature.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] Because of this temperature sensitivity, LED measurement standards, like IESNA’s LM-85 Archived 2017-10-18 at the Wayback Machine, require that the junction temperature is determined when making photometric measurements.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] Junction heating can be minimized in these devices by using the Continuous Pulse Test Method specified in LM-85.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/junction-temperature] An L-I sweep conducted with an Osram Yellow LED shows that Single Pulse Test Method measurements yield a 25% drop in luminous flux output and DC Test Method measurements yield a 70% drop.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] All electronic devices and circuitry generate excess heat and thus require **thermal management** to improve reliability and prevent premature failure.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The amount of heat output is equal to the power input, if there are no other energy interactions.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] There are several techniques for cooling including various styles of heat sinks, thermoelectric coolers, forced air systems and fans, heat pipes, and others.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] In cases of extreme low environmental temperatures, it may actually be necessary to heat the electronic components to achieve satisfactory operation.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] This is usually quoted as the thermal resistance from junction to case of the semiconductor device.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] For example, a heatsink rated at 10 °C/W will get 10 °C hotter than the surrounding air when it dissipates 1 Watt of heat.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Thus, a heatsink with a low °C/W value is more efficient than a heatsink with a high °C/W value.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Given two semiconductor devices in the same package, a lower junction to ambient resistance (RθJ-C) indicates a more efficient device.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] However, when comparing two devices with different die-free package thermal resistances (Ex.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] DirectFET MT vs wirebond 5x6mm PQFN), their junction to ambient or junction to case resistance values may not correlate directly to their comparative efficiencies.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] A heatsink's thermal mass can be considered as a capacitor (storing heat instead of charge) and the thermal resistance as an electrical resistance (giving a measure of how fast stored heat can be dissipated).
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Together, these two components form a thermal RC circuit with an associated time constant given by the product of R and C.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] This quantity can be used to calculate the dynamic heat dissipation capability of a device, in an analogous way to the electrical case.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] A **thermal interface material or mastic** (a.k.a.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] **TIM**) is used to fill the gaps between thermal transfer surfaces, such as between microprocessors and heatsinks, in order to increase thermal transfer efficiency.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] It has a higher thermal conductivity value in Z-direction than xy-direction.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Due to technological developments and public interest, the retail heat sink market rose high.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] In the early 2000s, CPUs were produced that emitted more and more heat than earlier, escalating requirements for quality cooling systems.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Overclocking has always meant greater cooling needs, and the inherently hotter chips meant more concerns for the enthusiast.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Efficient heat sinks are vital to overclocked computer systems because the higher a microprocessor's cooling rate, the faster the computer can operate without instability; generally, faster operation leads to higher performance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Many companies now compete to offer the best heat sink for PC overclocking enthusiasts.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Temporary heat sinks were sometimes used while soldering circuit boards, preventing excessive heat from damaging sensitive nearby electronics.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] In the simplest case, this means partially gripping a component using a heavy metal crocodile clip or similar clamp.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] On the other hand, electrical components such as magnetic reed switches can malfunction if exposed to higher powered soldering irons, so this practice is still very much in use.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Heat sinks are widely used in electronics and have become essential to modern microelectronics.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] In common use, it is a metal object brought into contact with an electronic component's hot surface—though in most cases, a thin thermal interface material mediates between the two surfaces.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Microprocessors and power handling semiconductors are examples of electronics that need a heat sink to reduce their temperature through increased thermal mass and heat dissipation (primarily by conduction and convection and to a lesser extent by radiation).
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Heat sinks have become almost essential to modern integrated circuits like microprocessors, DSPs, GPUs, and more.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] A heat sink usually consists of a metal structure with one or more flat surfaces to ensure good thermal contact with the components to be cooled, and an array of comb or fin like protrusions to increase the surface contact with the air, and thus the rate of heat dissipation.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] A heat sink is sometimes used in conjunction with a fan to increase the rate of airflow over the heat sink.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] This maintains a larger temperature gradient by replacing warmed air faster than convection would.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Placing a conductive thick metal plate, referred to as a cold plate, as a heat transfer interface between a heat source and a cold flowing fluid (or any other heat sink) may improve the cooling performance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] It is shown that the thick plate can significantly improve the heat transfer between the heat source and the cooling fluid by way of conducting the heat current in an optimal manner.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The two most attractive advantages of this method are that no additional pumping power and no extra heat transfer surface area, that is quite different from fins (extended surfaces).
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Heat sinks function by efficiently transferring thermal energy ("heat") from an object at high temperature to a second object at a lower temperature with a much greater heat capacity.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] This rapid transfer of thermal energy quickly brings the first object into thermal equilibrium with the second, lowering the temperature of the first object, fulfilling the heat sink's role as a cooling device.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Efficient function of a heat sink relies on rapid transfer of thermal energy from the first object to the heat sink, and the heat sink to the second object.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The most common design of a heat sink is a metal device with many fins.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The high thermal conductivity of the metal combined with its large surface area result in the rapid transfer of thermal energy to the surrounding, cooler, air.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] This cools the heat sink and whatever it is in direct thermal contact with.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Use of fluids (for example coolants in refrigeration) and thermal interface material (in cooling electronic devices) ensures good transfer of thermal energy to the heat sink.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Similarly, a fan may improve the transfer of thermal energy from the heat sink to the air.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] A heat sink usually consists of a base with one or more flat surfaces and an array of comb or fin-like protrusions to increase the heat sink's surface area contacting the air, and thus increasing the heat dissipation rate.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] While a heat sink is a static object, a fan often aids a heat sink by providing increased airflow over the heat sink—thus maintaining a larger temperature gradient by replacing the warmed air more quickly than passive convection achieves alone—this is known as a forced-air system.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Ideally, heat sinks are made from a good thermal conductor such as silver, gold, copper, or aluminum alloy.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Copper and aluminum are among the most-frequently used materials for this purpose within electronic devices.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Copper (401 W/(m·K) at 300 K) is significantly more expensive than aluminum (237 W/(m·K) at 300 K) but is also roughly twice as efficient as a thermal conductor.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Aluminum has the significant advantage that it can be easily formed by extrusion, thus making complex cross-sections possible.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Aluminum is also much lighter than copper, offering less mechanical stress on delicate electronic components.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Some heat sinks made from aluminum have a copper core as a trade off.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The heat sink's contact surface (the base) must be flat and smooth to ensure the best thermal contact with the object needing cooling.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Frequently a thermally conductive grease is used to ensure optimal thermal contact; such compounds often contain colloidal silver.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Further, a clamping mechanism, screws, or thermal adhesive hold the heat sink tightly onto the component, but specifically without pressure that would crush the component.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Heat sink performance (including free convection, forced convection, liquid cooled, and any combination thereof) is a function of material, geometry, and overall surface heat transfer coefficient.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Online heat sink calculators from companies such as Novel Concepts, Inc. and at www.heatsinkcalculator.com can accurately estimate forced and natural convection heat sink performance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] For more complex heat sink geometries, or heat sinks with multiple materials or multiple fluids, computation fluid dynamics (CFD) analysis is recommended (see graphics on this page).
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] This term describes device cooling by the convection currents of the warm air being allowed to escape the confines of the component to be replaced by cooler air.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Since warm air normally rises, this method usually requires venting at the top or sides of the casing to be effective.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] If there is more air being forced into a system than being pumped out (due to an imbalance in the number of fans), this is referred to as a 'positive' airflow, as the pressure inside the unit is higher than outside.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] A heat pipe is a heat transfer device that uses evaporation and condensation of a two-phase "working fluid" or coolant to transport large quantities of heat with a very small difference in temperature between the hot and cold interfaces.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] A typical heat pipe consists of sealed hollow tube made of a thermoconductive metal such as copper or aluminium, and a wick to return the working fluid from the evaporator to the condenser.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The pipe contains both saturated liquid and vapor of a working fluid (such as water, methanol or ammonia), all other gases being excluded.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The most common heat pipe for electronics thermal management has a copper envelope and wick, with water as the working fluid.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Copper/methanol is used if the heat pipe needs to operate below the freezing point of water, and aluminum/ammonia heat pipes are used for electronics cooling in space.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The advantage of heat pipes is their great efficiency in transferring heat.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The thermal conductivity of heat pipes can be as high as 100,000 W/m K, in contrast to copper, which has a thermal conductivity of around 400 W/m K.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] There are no moving parts, so a Peltier plate is maintenance free.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] It has a relatively low efficiency, so thermoelectric cooling is generally used for electronic devices, such as infra-red sensors, that need to operate at temperatures below ambient.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] For cooling these devices, the solid state nature of the Peltier plates outweighs their poor efficiency.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Thermoelectric junctions are typically around 10% as efficient as the ideal Carnot cycle refrigerator, compared with 40% achieved by conventional compression cycle systems.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] A synthetic jet is produced by a continual flow of vortices that are formed by alternating brief ejection and suction of air across an opening such that the net mass flux is zero.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] A unique feature of these jets is that they are formed entirely from the working fluid of the flow system in which they are deployed can produce a net momentum to the flow of a system without net mass injection to the system.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Synthetic jet air movers have no moving parts and are thus maintenance free.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Due to the high heat transfer coefficients, high reliability but lower overall flow rates, Synthetic jet air movers are usually used at the chip level and not at the system level for cooling.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] However depending on the size and complexity of the systems they can be used for both at times.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] An electrostatic fluid accelerator (EFA) is a device which pumps a fluid such as air without any moving parts.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Instead of using rotating blades, as in a conventional fan, an EFA uses an electric field to propel electrically charged air molecules.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Because air molecules are normally neutrally charged, the EFA has to create some charged molecules, or ions, first.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Thus there are three basic steps in the fluid acceleration process: ionize air molecules, use those ions to push many more neutral molecules in a desired direction, and then recapture and neutralize the ions to eliminate any net charge.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The basic principle has been understood for some time but only in recent years have seen developments in the design and manufacture of EFA devices that may allow them to find practical and economical applications, such as in micro-cooling of electronics components.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] More recently, high thermal conductivity materials such as synthetic diamond and boron arsenide cooling sinks are being researched to provide better cooling.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Boron arsenide has been reported with high thermal conductivity and high thermal boundary conductance with gallium nitride transistors and thus better performance than diamond and silicon carbide cooling technologies.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Department of Defense, research has been underway using high-power density gallium nitride transistors with synthetic diamonds as thermal conductors.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Also, some heat sinks are constructed of multiple materials with desirable characteristics, such as phase change materials, which can store a great deal of energy due to their heat of fusion.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Thermal simulations give engineers a visual representation of the temperature and airflow inside the equipment.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Thermal simulations enable engineers to design the cooling system; to optimise a design to reduce power consumption, weight and cost; and to verify the thermal design to ensure there are no issues when the equipment is built.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Most thermal simulation software uses Computational fluid dynamics techniques to predict temperature and airflow of an electronics system.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Thermal simulation is often required to determine how to effectively cool components within design constraints.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Simulation enables the design and verification of the thermal design of the equipment at a very early stage and throughout the design of the electronic and mechanical parts.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Designing with thermal properties in mind from the start reduces the risk of last minute design changes to fix thermal issues.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Using thermal simulation as part of the design process enables the creation of an optimal and innovative product design that performs to specification and meets customers' reliability requirements.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] It is easy to design a cooling system for almost any equipment if there is unlimited space, power and budget.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] However, the majority of equipment will have a rigid specification that leaves a limited margin for error.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] There is a constant pressure to reduce power requirements, system weight and cost parts, without compromising performance or reliability.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Thermal simulation allows experimentation with optimisation, such as modifying heatsink geometry or reducing fan speeds in a virtual environment, which is faster, cheaper and safer than physical experiment and measurement.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Traditionally, the first time the thermal design of the equipment is verified is after a prototype has been built.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The device is powered up, perhaps inside an environmental chamber, and temperatures of the critical parts of the system are measured using sensors such as thermocouples.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] If any problems are discovered, the project is delayed while a solution is sought.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] A change to the design of a PCB or enclosure part may be required to fix the issue, which will take time and cost a significant amount of money.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] If thermal simulation is used as part of the design process of the equipment, thermal design issue will be identified before a prototype is built.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Fixing an issue at the design stage is both quicker and cheaper than modifying the design after a prototype is created.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] There are a wide range of software tools that are designed for thermal simulation of electronics include 6SigmaET, Ansys' IcePak and Mentor Graphics' FloTHERM.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Thermal management measures must be taken to accommodate high heat release equipment in telecommunications rooms.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Generic supplemental/spot cooling techniques, as well as turnkey cooling solutions developed by equipment manufacturers are viable solutions.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Such solutions could allow very high heat release equipment to be housed in a central office that has a heat density at or near the cooling capacity available from the central air handler.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] According to Telcordia GR-3028, *Thermal Management in Telecommunications Central Offices,* the most common way of cooling modern telecommunications equipment internally is by utilizing multiple high-speed fans to create forced convection cooling.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Although direct and indirect liquid cooling may be introduced in the future, the current design of new electronic equipment is geared towards maintaining air as the cooling medium.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] A well-developed "holistic" approach is required to understand current and future thermal management problems.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Space cooling on one hand, and equipment cooling on the other, cannot be viewed as two isolated parts of the overall thermal challenge.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The main purpose of an equipment facility's air-distribution system is to distribute conditioned air in such a way that the electronic equipment is cooled effectively.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The overall cooling efficiency depends on how the air distribution system moves air through the equipment room, how the equipment moves air through the equipment frames, and how these airflows interact with one another.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] High heat-dissipation levels rely heavily on a seamless integration of equipment-cooling and room-cooling designs.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The existing environmental solutions in telecommunications facilities have inherent limitations.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] For example, most mature central offices have limited space available for large air duct installations that are required for cooling high heat density equipment rooms.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Furthermore, steep temperature gradients develop quickly should a cooling outage occur; this has been well documented through computer modeling and direct measurements and observations.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Although environmental backup systems may be in place, there are situations when they will not help.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] In a recent case, telecommunications equipment in a major central office was overheated, and critical services were interrupted by a complete cooling shut down initiated by a false smoke alarm.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] A major obstacle for effective thermal management is the way heat-release data is currently reported.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Suppliers generally specify the maximum (nameplate) heat release from the equipment.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] In reality, equipment configuration and traffic diversity will result in significantly lower heat release numbers.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] As stated in GR-3028, most equipment environments maintain cool front (maintenance) aisles and hot rear (wiring) aisles, where cool supply air is delivered to the front aisles and hot air is removed from the rear aisles.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] This scheme provides multiple benefits, including effective equipment cooling and high thermal efficiency.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] In the traditional room cooling class utilized by the majority of service providers, equipment cooling would benefit from air intake and exhaust locations that help move air from the front aisle to the rear aisle.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The traditional front-bottom to top-rear pattern, however, has been replaced in some equipment with other airflow patterns that may not ensure adequate equipment cooling in high heat density areas.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] A classification of equipment (shelves and cabinets) into Equipment-Cooling (EC) classes serves the purpose of classifying the equipment with regard to the cooling air intake and hot air exhaust locations, i.e., the equipment airflow schemes or protocols.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The EC-Class syntax provides a flexible and important “common language.” It is used for developing Heat-Release Targets (HRTs), which are important for network reliability, equipment and space planning, and infrastructure capacity planning.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] HRTs take into account physical limitations of the environment and environmental baseline criteria, including the supply airflow capacity, air diffusion into the equipment space, and air-distribution/equipment interactions.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] In addition to being used for developing the HRTs, the EC Classification can be used to show compliance on product sheets, provide internal design specifications, or specify requirements in purchase orders.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The Room-Cooling classification (RC-Class) refers to the way the overall equipment space is air-conditioned (cooled).
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] The main purpose of RC-Classes is to provide a logical classification and description of legacy and non-legacy room-cooling schemes or protocols in the central office environment.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] In addition to being used for developing HRTs, the RC-classification can be used in internal central office design specifications or in purchase orders.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Supplemental-Cooling classes (SC-Class) provide a classification of supplemental cooling techniques.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Service providers use supplemental/spot-cooling solutions to supplement the cooling capacity (e.g., to treat occurrences of “hot spots”) provided by the general room-cooling protocol as expressed by the RC-Class.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Energy consumption by telecommunications equipment currently accounts for a high percentage of the total energy consumed in central offices.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Most of this energy is subsequently released as heat to the surrounding equipment space.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] Since most of the remaining central office energy use goes to cool the equipment room, the economic impact of making the electronic equipment energy-efficient would be considerable for companies that use and operate telecommunications equipment.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-management-electronics] It would reduce capital costs for support systems, and improve thermal conditions in the equipment room.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] In heat transfer, thermal engineering, and thermodynamics**, thermal conductance** and **thermal resistance** are fundamental concepts that describe the ability of materials or systems to conduct heat and the opposition they offer to the heat current.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] The ability to manipulate these properties allows engineers to control temperature gradient, prevent thermal shock, and maximize the efficiency of thermal systems.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Furthermore, these principles find applications in a multitude of fields, including materials science, mechanical engineering, electronics, and energy management.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Knowledge of these principles is crucial in various scientific, engineering, and everyday applications, from designing efficient temperature control, thermal insulation, and thermal management in industrial processes to optimizing the performance of electronic devices.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Conversely, **thermal resistance** (*R*) measures the opposition to the heat current in a material or system.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] It is measured in units of kelvins per watt (K/W) and indicates how much temperature difference (in kelvins) is required to transfer a unit of heat current (in watts) through the material or object.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] It is essential to optimize the building insulation, evaluate the efficiency of electronic devices, and enhance the performance of heat sinks in various applications.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Objects made of insulators like rubber tend to have very high resistance and low conductance, while objects made of conductors like metals tend to have very low resistance and high conductance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] This relationship is quantified by resistivity or conductivity.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] However, the nature of a material is not the only factor as it also depends on the size and shape of an object because these properties are extensive rather than intensive.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] The relationship between thermal conductance and resistance is analogous to that between electrical conductance and resistance in the domain of electronics.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Electronics cooling: Thermal resistance is crucial for designing heat sinks and thermal management systems in electronic devices to prevent overheating.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Calculating thermal conductance is crucial for designing effective heat sinks and cooling systems in electronic devices.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Automotive design: Automotive engineers use thermal resistance to optimize the cooling system and prevent overheating in engines and other vehicle components.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Evaluating thermal resistance helps in designing engine components and automotive cooling systems.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Cookware design: Thermal conductance is important for designing cookware to ensure even heat distribution and cooking efficiency.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Assessing thermal conductance is important in designing cookware for even heat distribution.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Heat exchangers: In industries like HVAC and chemical processing, heat exchangers use thermal conductance to efficiently transfer heat between fluids.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Aerospace: In spacecraft and aircraft, thermal resistance and conductance are critical for managing temperature variations in extreme environments.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Designing spacecraft and aviation systems require considerations of thermal conductance and resistance to manage temperature extremes.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Cryogenics: Understanding thermal properties is vital for the design of cryogenic systems used in superconductors and medical applications.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Energy efficiency: In the energy sector, thermal resistance and conductance play a role in designing efficient heat exchangers for power plants and energy-efficient appliances.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Medical devices: Thermal management is crucial for medical equipment like magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) machines and laser systems to maintain precise operating temperatures.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Ensuring proper thermal management is crucial for the safety and performance of medical devices and laser systems.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Food processing: The food industry uses knowledge of thermal conductance to optimize processes like pasteurization and cooking and design equipment for food processing, such as ovens and refrigeration units.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Materials science: Researchers use thermal conductance data to develop new materials for various applications, including energy storage and advanced coatings.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Environmental science: Thermal resistance is considered in climate studies to understand heat transfer in Earth's atmosphere and oceans.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Evaluating thermal resistance is useful in studying soil temperature profiles for environmental and agricultural research.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC): Understanding thermal resistance aids in optimizing heating, ventilation, and air conditioning systems for better energy efficiency.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Thermal packaging: Ensuring proper thermal conductance and resistance is crucial for protecting sensitive goods during transport.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Solar energy systems: Understanding thermal resistance is important in the design of solar collectors and thermal energy storage systems.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Manufacturing processes: Controlling thermal conductance is essential in processes like welding, heat treatment, and metal casting.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Geothermal energy: Assessing thermal conductance is important in geothermal heat exchangers and energy production.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Thermal imaging: Infrared cameras and thermal imaging devices use principles of thermal conductance to detect temperature variations.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Absolute thermal resistance is the temperature difference across a structure when a unit of heat energy flows through it in unit time.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] It is the reciprocal of thermal conductance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] The SI unit of absolute thermal resistance is kelvins per watt (K/W) or the equivalent degrees Celsius per watt (°C/W) – the two are the same since the intervals are equal: Δ*T* = 1 K = 1 °C.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] The thermal resistance of materials is of great interest to electronic engineers because most electrical components generate heat and need to be cooled.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Electronic components malfunction or fail if they overheat, and some parts routinely need measures taken in the design stage to prevent this.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Electrical engineers are familiar with Ohm's law and so often use it as an analogy when doing calculations involving thermal resistance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Mechanical and structural engineers are more familiar with Hooke's law and so often use it as an analogy when doing calculations involving thermal resistance.
