[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Consider a component such as a silicon transistor that is bolted to the metal frame of a piece of equipment.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] The transistor's manufacturer will specify parameters in the datasheet called the *absolute thermal resistance from junction to case* (symbol: $R_{\theta {\rm {JC}}}$ ), and the maximum allowable temperature of the semiconductor junction (symbol: $T_{J{\rm {max}}}$ ).
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] The specification for the design should include a maximum temperature at which the circuit should function correctly.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Finally, the designer should consider how the heat from the transistor will escape to the environment: this might be by convection into the air, with or without the aid of a heat sink, or by conduction through the printed circuit board.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] For simplicity, let us assume that the designer decides to bolt the transistor to a metal surface (or heat sink) that is guaranteed to be less than $\Delta T_{\rm {HS}}$ above the ambient temperature.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Given all this information, the designer can construct a model of the heat flow from the semiconductor junction, where the heat is generated, to the outside world.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] In our example, the heat has to flow from the junction to the case of the transistor, then from the case to the metalwork.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] We do not need to consider where the heat goes after that, because we are told that the metalwork will conduct heat fast enough to keep the temperature less than $\Delta T_{\rm {HS}}$ above ambient: this is all we need to know.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] Suppose the engineer wishes to know how much power can be put into the transistor before it overheats.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] where $R_{\theta {\rm {B}}}$ is the absolute thermal resistance of the bond between the transistor's case and the metalwork.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] This figure depends on the nature of the bond - for example, a thermal bonding pad or thermal transfer grease might be used to reduce the absolute thermal resistance.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] The designer now knows ${\dot {Q}}_{\rm {max}}$ , the maximum power that the transistor can be allowed to dissipate, so they can design the circuit to limit the temperature of the transistor to a safe level.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] This means that the transistor can dissipate about 18 watts before it overheats.
[src:thermal-management-electronics/thermal-resistance] A cautious designer would operate the transistor at a lower power level to increase its reliability.
